TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Relationship of Personal Influence Dissonance to Job Tension, Satisfaction and Involvement
AU  - Hollon, C. J.
AU  - Chesser, R. J.
Y1  - 1976/06/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255780
DO  - 10.5465/255780
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 308
EP  - 314
VL  - 19
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article presents a study on the dissonance theory, which has been designed to specify under what conditions the dissonance prediction will hold. There are three untested hypotheses that emerged when personal influence in decision making applying to the immediate work environment is conceptualized within the concept of dissonance theory. Hypothesis include that the dissonance is positively associated with job related tension. The other two hypotheses deal with the negative influence of dissonance with overall job satisfaction and job involvement. The results implies that the prediction holds when an individual experiences a difference in the actual and desired level of influence in the job situation.
AB  - This article presents a study on the dissonance theory, which has been designed to specify under what conditions the dissonance prediction will hold. There are three untested hypotheses that emerged when personal influence in decision making applying to the immediate work environment is conceptualized within the concept of dissonance theory. Hypothesis include that the dissonance is positively associated with job related tension. The other two hypotheses deal with the negative influence of dissonance with overall job satisfaction and job involvement. The results implies that the prediction holds when an individual experiences a difference in the actual and desired level of influence in the job situation.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255780
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/255780
Y2  - 2026/04/24
