TY  - JOUR
T1  - Research Notes. Information Relevant to the Task in the Risky Shift Phenomenon
AU  - Morgan, Cyril P.
AU  - Beatty, Richard W.
Y1  - 1976/06/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255779
DO  - 10.5465/255779
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 304
EP  - 308
VL  - 19
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article examines the influence of key arguments in interpreting the information-relevant-to-the-task hypothesis. It argues that the discovery of a particularly persuasive argument favoring an alternative leads to the risky shift phenomenon. Given the justification that group discussion leads subjects to discover ways of minimizing possible losses and thus influences the choice of alternatives, the hypothesis still failed. A possibility is that the hypothesis was overextended when used for caution-oriented problems.
AB  - This article examines the influence of key arguments in interpreting the information-relevant-to-the-task hypothesis. It argues that the discovery of a particularly persuasive argument favoring an alternative leads to the risky shift phenomenon. Given the justification that group discussion leads subjects to discover ways of minimizing possible losses and thus influences the choice of alternatives, the hypothesis still failed. A possibility is that the hypothesis was overextended when used for caution-oriented problems.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/255779
