TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Survey of Managerial Interests with Respect to Conflict
AU  - Thomas, Kenneth W.
AU  - Schmidt, Warren H.
Y1  - 1976/06/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/255781
DO  - 10.5465/255781
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 315
EP  - 318
VL  - 19
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article presents the results of a survey conducted by the American Management Association regarding the managerial interests in the area of conflict and conflict management. Studies on conflict have become popular management topics and have provided a range of content for education and training. Moreover, organizations now include conflict management in their training programs. As presented in the article, the outcome of the survey clearly suggest that managers from middle to top levels have an active and growing interest in learning more about both the prevention and management of conflict.
AB  - This article presents the results of a survey conducted by the American Management Association regarding the managerial interests in the area of conflict and conflict management. Studies on conflict have become popular management topics and have provided a range of content for education and training. Moreover, organizations now include conflict management in their training programs. As presented in the article, the outcome of the survey clearly suggest that managers from middle to top levels have an active and growing interest in learning more about both the prevention and management of conflict.
